What You Don’t Know Might Hurt You: Possible Dangers of Assuming A Fixed ICC Across Treatment Arms

DRAFT / WORK IN PROGRESS

Josh Nugent

# Load required packages, preprocess the data
library(tidyverse)
library(pander)
alpha_cost2000 <- readRDS("alpha_cost2000.rds")
alpha_cost1000 <- readRDS("alpha_cost1000.rds")
dat_long <- alpha_cost2000 %>% mutate(TIE_naive = T1E_dumb, TIE_flexible = T1E_best) %>% select(-T1E_smart, -T1E_best, -T1E_dumb) %>% gather(key = type, value = TIE, 8:9)

Defining our terms

In this document I’ll refer to the Type I error rate where the data analyst fits a model that does not allow for different ICCs across treatment arms as the “naive TIE rate”. Allowing for different ICCs by arm will be called the “flexible” approach.

Comparing naive and flexible, marginalizing over all ICC value combinations

First, here is all of the data for this run of 2000 simulations - various combinations of cluster size, number of clusters, and icc values by arm. Here you can see that the naive TIE rate is always greater than or equal to the flexible TIE rate.

ggplot(data = alpha_cost2000) +
  geom_point(aes(x = T1E_best, y = T1E_dumb, color = as.factor(nsub), shape = as.factor(nclust))) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0) +
  labs(x = "Flexible TIE rate", y = "Naive TIE rate")

The shapes are a little hard to see, so let’s zoom in on one cluster size. You can see that smaller clusters have more variability; not surprising. However, they also skew conservative, which is a bit more surprising.

ggplot(data = alpha_cost2000 %>% filter(nsub == 50)) +
  geom_point(aes(x = T1E_best, y = T1E_dumb, color = as.factor(nclust))) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0) +
  labs(x = "Flexible TIE rate", y = "Naive TIE rate")

Looking at the distribution across different cluster sizes and number of clusters, you can see that NLME is a bit conservative when the values are small:

Examining naive method across different ICC combinations

First, one specific example: 10 subjects per cluster, 10 clusters per arm. ICC values are the rows and columns. This is the TIE for just the naive method.

table1 <- alpha_cost2000 %>% filter(nsub == 10, nclust == 10) %>%
  select(T1E_dumb, icc1, icc2) %>%
  spread(icc1, T1E_dumb) %>% 
  remove_rownames %>% column_to_rownames(var="icc2")
pander(table1)
  0.001 0.01 0.02 0.05 0.1 0.2
0.001 0.02677 0.0267 0.03696 0.04139 0.04066 0.05556
0.01 0.03218 0.03778 0.03873 0.0449 0.04024 0.058
0.02 0.03365 0.03873 0.04064 0.0367 0.0437 0.04714
0.05 0.04254 0.03469 0.05015 0.04422 0.04254 0.0475
0.1 0.04805 0.04058 0.04108 0.03908 0.05058 0.052
0.2 0.0595 0.04652 0.05005 0.057 0.042 0.04402

A little hard to see what’s going on with just numbers. Let’s look at it as a heat map, again just the naive method:

ggplot(data = alpha_cost2000 %>% filter(nsub == 10, nclust == 10)) +
  geom_tile(aes(x = as.factor(icc1), y = as.factor(icc2), fill = T1E_dumb)) +
  labs(title = "10 observations per cluster, 10 clusters per arm", x = "ICC1", y = "ICC2")

It seems that the error rate is too high as cluster imbalance rises, which makes sense, but also rises as the ICC rises along the diagonal. More simulations are running now to see if this pattern holds up. In the meantime, let’s look at the marginal heat map above across all values of cluster size / # of clusters that we have.

margdata <- alpha_cost2000 %>% select(icc1, icc2, T1E_dumb) %>% group_by(icc1, icc2) %>% summarise(mean(T1E_dumb)) %>% ungroup %>% mutate(TIE_naive = `mean(T1E_dumb)`) %>% select(-`mean(T1E_dumb)`)
ggplot(data = margdata) +
  geom_tile(aes(x = as.factor(icc1), y = as.factor(icc2), fill = TIE_naive)) +
  labs(title = "All # cluster / cluster size combinations", x = "ICC1", y = "ICC2") +
  scale_fill_gradient(limits = c(.025, .055))

It looks like the pattern we suspected is holding up.

Examining flexible method across different ICC combinations

Will switching to the flexible method improve the outcomes?

margdata2 <- alpha_cost2000 %>% select(icc1, icc2, T1E_best) %>% group_by(icc1, icc2) %>% summarise(mean(T1E_best)) %>% ungroup %>% mutate(TIE_flexible = `mean(T1E_best)`) %>% select(-`mean(T1E_best)`)
ggplot(data = margdata2) +
  geom_tile(aes(x = as.factor(icc1), y = as.factor(icc2), fill = TIE_flexible)) +
  labs(title = "All # cluster / cluster size combinations", x = "ICC1", y = "ICC2") +
  scale_fill_gradient(limits = c(.025, .055))

It seems that the pattern holds even with the flexible method, though the error rates in question are lower across the board.

One final note on methods

All of the above assumed a fixed \(\sigma^2\) by arm - the ICC was varied just by changing \(\sigma^2_b\). Hence, we could use lme4 for this, and then extend to GLMMs instead of just LMMs using glmer. Alternatively, we can look at the impact of different \(\sigma^2\) values across arms.
